segments.text: Is there that similar spree at West Point?
Sure.
Would you compare them?
Are there any differences?
As far as spirit?
No.
The spirit is the same.
They both have come in the same.
Well, they have a 1,200-meter team up there.
It's not just 11 on the field.
It's 1,200 of them.
It used to be 1,200.
There's a lot more than that now.
We have pep rallies the same way.
Everybody's motivated.
And it catches the same spirit, school spirit.
It's strong.
We had the same at Tarleton, Florida.
We had the same school spirit there too.
Yeah, the same as strong at Tarleton as you did at A&M.
Yeah, only we had girls.
Yeah, there's a difference there.
And they've got girls at A&M now too.
Sure do.
And they've got girls at West Point now too.
What's your opinion of that?
Well, I was skeptical at first, but I think I'm a supporter.
At West Point and A&M?
Yes.
Were you a leader in the Corps of Cadets?
You certainly weren't in the Corps of Cadets, but were you a leader later at West Point?
Yes.
Well, were you telling anyone?
Well, I was the selected as the highest ranking.
Cleave in my company.
And I was the senior.
Is that it?
My junior year, I was number one in my class in the military.
I guess I was in line to be the first captain.
So you always had those positions of leadership.
Now, what do the cadets at West Point think of A&M?
Well, most of them don't know a great deal about it, except they know of it.
It's been advertised a lot by those of us that attended.
Did they ask you a lot of questions?
Were they at all interested?
Well, it seemed like they were more interested after they got to know something.
And they knew.
They've known a lot of them, and they think a lot of them.
Congratulations.
Of course, you probably sat on promotion boards throughout your career.
Was there any favoritism one way or the other?
No.
Where a man went to school, very little.
They had nothing.
I'd say almost nothing.
What they've accomplished, how they've performed.
I could see no changes based on that.
No training or anything else.
No, I've heard from some people that there's this West Point Protective Association, like a pile of crap.
Okay, well, why?
Tell me.
Well, I've seen it operate.
I've seen promotion boards.
It goes beyond even that.
Even close friends.
It would not influence the decision.
You pick the guy that you think can do the job, or you promote the guy that you think is the best man.
I don't know.
I just don't buy it.
It's been a sort of protective association, a ring knocker, whatever you want to call it.
Is there tension, though, between West Point officers and ROTC officers in the military?
I didn't see military.
I didn't sense that.
Okay.
Would you compare the quality of students at Tarleton and Anaheim, the ROTC schools,
the quality of student attendance at West Point?
Well, I would say that the new entrance exams that all of them are using, they're going to be awful complicated.
Were they comparable?
No.
There was no such thing.
Anybody could go to A&M or Tarleton.
They had to pass an entrance exam.
It was quite hard to show a certain level in college that they had accomplished to get exempt from taking an entrance exam.
So which place do you think were superior students?
That doesn't make them superior students.
They're more selective in who can get in.
They were selective.
But in order to get into Carleton or A&M, all you had to do was be a high school graduate.
I think it's changed now.
But did you have an opinion about your colleagues?
Which ones?
Worked harder, got better grades.
Well, after a guy gets through the first year at the military, he gets through.
He's got another thing.
He's proved he's got enough intelligence to pass the rest of them, in my opinion, because he's done it under pressure.
And there are probably fewer of them to flunk out at West Point after the first year than on the other side.
I'm only surmising this because I'm not familiar with what goes on in Tarleton or in, well, I am a little bit from Tarleton, but not in A&M.
I'm not familiar with the figures or the problems that they're having.
I'm just not familiar with it now.
What did you decide to...
You said that you received the appointment at West Point.
At this time you were about a junior standing.
Why did you decide to leave A&M with only about one year left of school and go to four more at West Point?
I decided I wanted to make the Army my group.
Oh, you did?
If I was going to do that, I wanted to be on the grounds floor.
I knew that if I didn't get in West Point, I was going to try for a commission in the Army Reserve.
In other words, you switched your
your aims from being an engineer and going to MIT to becoming a regular Army?
Yeah, a regular Army.
Now, why did you switch your aims?
Well, as I told you, I had an influence as a major vendor on Charlton Thorold and the
These two guys, my parents, and another second lieutenant, just got out.
They impressed me very much.
Very impressed with them.
They walked straight, stood tall.
Everybody looked up to them.
So it was basically because of a couple of people that influenced you?
Yeah.
I made the decision.
They told me I had the point.
That's when I made the decision.
What was your response when you found that you had the appointment?
I was late.
I thought at the time, I knew I didn't want to be a farmer.
I'd seen my grandfather.
Sure.
Sit on the porch and cry.
Cotton was washed away, and my dad was in the construction business.
Totally dependent on the weather.
I thought I wanted to do the same thing.
A little less dependent on what happened, nature-wise.
So, in other words, you wanted the security of a military crew?
Well, not only the security, but the excitement.
How did you know it was exciting?
Well, these lieutenants talked to me about it.
So they told you your experiences, and you identified with those?
Yeah.
Okay.
Why did you decide to go from Army infantry, which you previously had planned on, and then change to flying in the Air Corps?
September 1941, and they decided to move our graduation date up six months.
They also decided to allow those who wanted to take Air Corps training to take Air Corps training, and they sold me on it.
Sold me on the opportunity.
And I had my first tactical officer at Major Harper.
He retired as a general.
He was my tactical officer and he encouraged me.
And I did.
But did you, did you, of course we needed, not only did we need fliers, but we needed infantry officers during the war.
Were you at all thrilled about the idea of being an aviator?
There was a lot of glamour in the late 1930s about aviation.
Were you at all interested now?
Well, we got, we were indoctrinated on the Air Force there, and we studied, and we were given orientation, pride.
I decided I'd like to be a pilot.
I knew we were going to war, and if I was going to war, I'd just as soon ride and walk.
What kind of pilot did you want to be?
Fighter pilot.
And you had no problem with the physical?
No.
Let's start then about your career.
When did you get your commission, second lieutenant?
19th of January, 1943.
I got my wings on December 10th, 42.
So you had your wings before you had your own class that wore their wings at West Point.
No kidding.
The first class was shorter.
The class after us graduated and got their wings on the same day they graduated.
And you went down, your first flight school, flying school, was down
And then June 42 to December 42 at Hicks Field in Fort Worth, right?
Went to Hicks Field in June of 42.
Mm-hmm.
It just lasted three months.
Mm-hmm.
So you had three months of flight school.
No, in primary, and then we went to basic.
I went to basic at West Point and then went back to play football.
Tell me about the flight school during the war.
Was it adequate?
Did it prepare you not to be a fighter pilot?
I thought it was very adequate.
And we had haze in there, too.
Oh, kidding?
Oh, yeah.
You could never escape, could you?
You got it every place.
All aviation cadets got haze.
It wasn't near as bad as...
There was plenty of them.
It was under control.
Physical or mental?
Both.
Who hazed you?
You were only there for three months?
The upperclassmen.
People that had been there for two months?
Well, we were 42K, and the 42J was there, still there.
They were the upperclassmen.
I don't think we were there for six weeks.
Six weeks, and then six weeks of basic.
I don't remember the number of weeks.
Anyhow, basic.
We started in June.
We had our wings in six months.
So it must have been about two months at each place.
Now tell me about black training.
What exactly was the training on?
Well, you had ground school, which covered theory and weather and subjects like that.
And then you started the flight training, went along with it.
You had ground school and flight training.
And you were assigned to an instructor.
And he took you up and demonstrated things to you and had you do them.
After you've been up so far, and they give you a checkride, and you checked out all right, you'd get out and let you solo.
After how long could you solo?
Six or eight hours, somewhere.
Six or eight hours of instruction, and they already had you soloing?
Yeah.
Did you feel that the flight school was adequate, free or freer, when you were late?
Oh, yeah, I know it was tremendous.
I really did.
I'll never forget the first day.

mean not the first day the first day we went out so i didn't see this guy hicks feeling forward man you're going out into the area today for the first time don't let any clouds get between you and hicks field if an airplane comes up to you and does a series of dives and zoom return to hicks field and land immediately
My good friends are there with me now, and I always recite that to each other.
We remember that so vividly.
And I remember the first time my instructor did a spin, I thought the airplane was going to come apart.
No kidding.
You were scared.
Well, it scared me, yeah.
But I didn't know what a spin was until he did it.
I knew what a spin was, but I'd never experienced one.
Were there many casualties during the training period?
I mean, did you lose many of your cadets?
Yes, quite a few washed out.
Not as many of the ones from West Point as the regular aviation cadets, because most of them then were nothing but high school graduates.
And they were much younger and inexperienced.
Well, we had some of our group washed out, too.
They had no ability to apply.
What about deaths?
Did you have very many?
No, not many.
Just a couple?
I don't recall us having any in primary or basic.
One of my classmates was killed in advance.
We were one of the first experimental classes.
They let us fly our fighters 10 hours before we graduated.
We were flying the B-39, and one of my classmates spun in.
I don't know what happened.
Then you went on in January 1943.
We went back to West Point on December 10th of January 1943 and we had our senior year.
So you had your senior year for six months?
No, six weeks.
Oh, for six weeks you had your whole senior year?
Well, obviously the necessity of war.
What'd you think about having a nine or ten month course in six weeks?
How'd they ever do that?
Well, they just condensed the courses and gave you what they could.
There's military history and law, military law.
Was there any grumbling from the students?
No, we were happy to leave.
That's what I thought.
Were you eager to get to war?
Yes.
Is that the feeling at West Point?
Yes.
I wanted to get in action.
Okay, so in April 1943, you didn't get in action.
You went to the 323rd Fighter Squadron.
and then at Langley also.
Here you have, for the next year, April 43 to 44, you were at four different bases.
Why is that?
Why do you keep moving your own?
Well, that's part of the program.
You move from place to place, and you have a different mission in each place and different training.
We did strafing at Langley at the Langley Range, and then we went up to New Jersey.
air-to-air gunnery out on the ocean.
And we were also, at all these places, we were flying air defense.
We were protecting capital.
And we were intercepting bogey under training conditions.
And we had people setting actual alert in Washington.
Thank you for that.
There never was, I don't know.
There was never an enemy aircraft.
That was never sighted, was there?
No.
We did sight some submarines.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
No kidding.
Did you ever fire on one?
No.
We weren't allowed to.
Why not?
I don't know.
They were, were they enemy or were they, you could never identify them?
No, we just told them where we saw them and they took it from there.
Mm-hmm.
So they might have been American.
They could have been.
When did you finally get overseas?
We got over in October 1943.
Okay, October 1943.
And what division were you with?
What was your job?
I was an element leader in the flag.
What type of aircraft?
And where did they send you?
They sent us to England.
So this is in preparation for Normandy.
At that time it wasn't.
We were in the 8th Air Force, and we flew escort for the bombers.
But then in, I think it was February,
They formed the 9th Air Force.
We were one of the original groups, and we changed bases.
We started preparation.
And we started dive bombing on buzz bomb sites and rocket sites and airfields and bridges and trains and whatever.
Did you work with any RIL?
Well, I suppose we did, but not our group.
Side by side?
Not side by side, not our group.
What did you think of the British people?
We liked them.
We thought they were very difficult to work with if you had anything to deal with.
civilian hierarchy, the clerk of the works, because they had so many rules and regulations they had to follow.
Well and I impossible now.
I wasn't in on that.
All I could hear was the guys talking about it.
Sure.
They had to.
We were doing nothing but fire.
How often did you fly on these attacks and on the bomber missions?
Well, I mean the group flew almost every day.
And how many fighter planes were in the group?
Well, we flew 16 airplanes per squadron, so we had 48 aircraft in the group, but we had more than that, aircraft and pilots assigned.
And so one squadron would fly every day, usually?
Well, all three squadrons, when we started, all three squadrons would fly every day.
A group would fly.
And then after we got in the 9th Air Force, we no longer flew group missions.
We flew squadron missions.
The strafing?
Strafing, bomb, dive bomb, strafing.
They told us when we got over there, when we were escorted, we shouldn't go over 20,000 feet.
Yeah, we weren't supposed to go below 20,000 feet because the ME-109, the Focke-Wulf 190 would shoot us down.
And I recall on the second mission I went on, I was flying the element on the wing commander.
We had some Focke-Wulf 190s come and
go through the formation, and I peeled off on the one that came through us and followed him.
And I went on down to about 15,000 feet, and I fired.
He was already away from me.
And I got my wingman and compressibility, which was the problem.
People would get too fast and get controlled for the first time.
And when I came back and got back up in formation, got back out on the ground, I was chewed out for going above 20,000 feet.
And then about two or three months later, when we went to the 9th Air Force, we never got above 15,000 feet for the rest of the war.
When the bombers bombed, they bombed about 20,000?
No, they were above 20.
There were more up by 30.
The flak was pretty bad.
Yeah.
I remember my first mission.
We took off and we had to climb through clouds.
As soon as we got airborne, we were in the clouds.
We didn't break out of it until we were over 20,000 feet and we already crossed over the coast.
I looked back and I saw all this flak come up there, and I said, man, this is war.
Until then, I hadn't seen any evidence of war, but I saw it then.
What were your feelings?
Well, you get a feeling of fear and respect right quick.
And then...
on some of the missions that we got to escort.
We'd read about them the next day and the stars would strike.
It made me feel sort of proud to be a part of it.
Now, were most of the bomber missions directed toward Germany by that time?
Yes, most of them were in Germany, although some of them were Still in France?
Some of them were in France and in Northern Europe.
Most of them at that time.
On your missions, I didn't see it on here, how many kills did you have?
I didn't have any kills.
Why not?
I never got the opportunity.
OK. What did you think of?
Did you think that that was kind of strange?
That you didn't see them?
No.
Why?
There were plenty of them that lots of people didn't see.
Well, you just had to be at the right place at the right time, and it's not unusual.
I only fired one, and that was on about my third or fourth mission or something like that.
I never saw another one.
In other words, by 1943 Except on the ground.
Yeah, by 1943 or 1944, the number of German airplanes was reduced.
Well, we were transferred to the 9th Air Force, and the 8th Air Force then got the P-51s, and they started picking them up, really.
And they are the ones protecting the bombers, and they were coming after the bombers, but they didn't send any fighters after us.
Because we were low-level, low-level dive bombers.
And not too far into France, even.
So they didn't have any airplanes that bothered us.
When you got there in 1943, what do you think was the opinion of our American fighter planes versus the Germans?
Well, in altitude, we were better.
And the low altitude capability of the P-47
We thought that the ME-109 and the Focke-Wulf 109 could out-turn us, but we could outrun them.
What about our armaments, firepower?
Well, we had eight machine guns, and they didn't have that much armament.
We had the good armament.
We thought we had a little better armament anyway.
The P-38, I don't think that it survived.
They did use them on reconnaissance, but they didn't survive.
As a matter of fact, when we went into France, we went to
place near Nancy, and he took over an old German airfield, and in the walls of their officer's club it showed pictures of Focke-Wulf 190s shooting down P-38s.
It's very interesting.
What was your general opinion of the quality of the
We had real good pilots.
But we were well trained.
But we didn't think much of the leadership down there.
No.
Because they could have bombed on the right end of the submission.
Instead, they chose to bomb churches and things like that.
It used to make the British mad.
And they lost the Battle of Britain.
But you thought as far as the pilots were concerned, they were as well trained, better trained, compared with the Americans?
No, I don't think they were better trained than the Americans.
They probably weren't as well trained as the Americans.
Some of them were very experienced, and they had some they were not.
I think overall our training was better.
That is initial training.
And of course the British were well trained too.
They had lots of experience.
Did you go on any exercises with the RAF?
Did you ever work with the British pilots in any of the striking missions?
No?
Always a general opinion of the RAF pilots.
Well, we thought they were good pilots.
We didn't get to associate with them.
You know about the fourth, right?
The fourth.
It was Americans who were with the R.E.F.
when they transferred to the U.S.A. after we got over there.
Were you happy to change from bomber missions, where you were a fighter protection for bombers, to strafing?
No, we wanted to shoot down some airplanes.
We were doing nothing but dive bombing and strafing.
It was exciting.
I can imagine.
Plenty of flak.
We had plenty of losses, too.
And this was the period of, what was this?
D.D.
Yeah, it was the period before D.D., yeah, before the Normandy invasion.
Were you then, you were bombing basically, or strafing and bombing, dive bombing, basically French
Anything that looked like supplies.
Yeah, and we grew up a lot of bridges.
We tried, and what we did was try to cut all the railroads and all the big bridges all the way around Paris.
Sure.
Coming towards Normandy.
Mm-hmm.
And, uh, in a media.
In marshland yards, we had lots of marshland yards.
And, uh, as I say, these, uh,
places that were launching missiles, B-1, B-2.
Now how could you identify those places?
They, uh, intelligence, and they took pictures, reconnaissance, took pictures and bring you, bring you back a picture to show you, to show you what to do.
And give you the coordinates?
Oh yeah.
And did you get any of those?
Oh yes, lots of them.
And did they, were they the type of, when you exploded them, or when you hit them, did they explode, or did they just?
No, they didn't explode.
They just fell over?
Well, they blew up.
You had craters.
How successful do you think you were in your task?
Well, we think we were highly successful.
I think that's what made the invasion go.
At any time did you work with Curtis LeMay?
No.
Did you later work with him when he was in charge of Sion?
Because he was over in the European theater.
Yes, I knew who he was.
He was a big airport guy.
After we left, it was night there.
Who was your commander?
I don't know, Whalen.
Whalen?
Yeah.
How was he?
Tremendous.
Tremendous.
Tremendous.
In what way?
Well, he came by to see us and talk to us and encouraged us, inspired us.
He'd come around, pin medals on people, things like that, talk to you.
I saw that we got what we needed.
Was there any problem with shortages in supplies?
No.
How about food?
We didn't like the food in front of the shortage.
But you always had enough bombs, and you always had enough ammunition, and the airplanes were well-maintained.
I mean, as well as they could be under wartime conditions.
Only one thing that I remember, the first time one of the B-1s, we were on the route right down through Maidstone, which is down on the south of Southwest.
We were right on the route when the V-1s came over to go to London.
The first one that came over, the Coastal Artillery, I mean, I guess it was whoever, the Coastal Artillery, I guess, was the one that was running the anti-aircraft around the base.
They shot up all their ammunition and all the reserves.
The first night one of them came over and they never did hit one.
So did you have to scramble?
Did you shoot those down?
Yes, we shot a few of them down.
Did you ever get the opportunity to hit one?
No.
Sometimes you were just lucky if you were coming back from a mission, one would be coming over so that you could chase it.
And you'd see it.
And you'd see it.
Or you'd already be on the ground and want to go around and say, oh, well, you missed that one.
But a couple of guys shot a few of them, shot one down.
You picked them up on radar?
We didn't have any right now.
But I mean the British could pick them up.
No, they were low level.
They couldn't pick them up that low.
They came in right over.
They were right on the deck.
About 50 feet or so.
Maybe 100.
They were really exciting.
I was wondering if you ever got shot down.
Yes, I got shot down once.
Can you tell me about that?
Yes, we went in and
We went in to dive on.
We went in to dive on.
And one place on the coast across from Dover there called Gray Graveling,
G-R-A-V-E-L-I-N-E-S. And they always sent up about a burst of flak, about four or five bursts, every time you went near them.
And we always asked when we got towards this particular day, we were at 12,000 feet, coming out after having dive-bombed an airfield or a launching site.
And good.
I think this one was in Airfield.
In northern France.
Yeah.
And we came back over and the flight leader, instead of passing when we got near this place, went straight over and a burst of flak came up in the hip.
One burst hit the knee right in the engine.
Was it below you when that exploded?
And the big fan quit turning.
And it got awfully quiet.
And that's the thing that impressed me.
It was so quiet.
So I started gliding.
And I got down to about 2,000 feet.
And I decided I'd better jump out.
I remember it was so big.
Always when I got out there.
Were you still over land?
I was over the North Sea, over water.
So you were over in the English Channel Zone?
Yeah, all the time, because that's the gravelings right on that host.
Anyhow, I unbuckled my parachute strap like I always did and started to get out.
And I said, well, that's silly.
You're supposed to try to sit back down and buckle my parachute.
And about that time, I was getting pretty low, and so I just stood up on it and jumped out.
So you opened up the canopy and jumped out.
Mm-hmm.
We'd been told the problem was hitting the tail, so what I did was step up on the side and jump as high as I could.
And then I made it.
Pulled my parachute, and this strap that comes across here came up and hit me in the nose and bludged my nose.
I tried to guide myself, and I made the dry land about 50 yards.
And it's minefields all around there, so of course what you do is you wait for the British to come get you.
So I waited for the British and pretty soon they came out in a jeep and picked me up.
And I got blood on that parachute, so that was ruined, so they gave me the parachute.
And my wife's wedding dress was made out of that parachute.
You were lucky to float over to England, weren't you?
Or did you try to keep gliding until you could see the land?
Well, I could see the land.
I could see the land.
It's not very far across there anyway.
I was very lucky to be able to make it that far.
You were lucky the wind wasn't blowing the other way, too.
It made me mad.
That was the next mission that day.
I was supposed to be the first one that I had led, the whole group.
The whole group on the mission.
And now you didn't have a plane.
I didn't have a plane.
I wasn't even there.
I got back over there and the group commander, I got back in time to go, but the group commander said no.
Said she'd go and leave and go to London.
So I did.
That's pretty exciting.
I bet you it was exciting.
I bet you it was really exciting.
How often did you get leads into London?
Oh, they called it R&R.
Yeah.
Maybe every couple of months or something.
Three days passed.
R&R.
How did the people in London treat the Americans?
They treated us very nice, I thought.
I remember one night, they had a blackout, of course.
A taxi cab came along and stopped and asked me for directions.
Sorry, I'm a stranger here.
But when you were June 6, 1944, were you directly involved with D-Day on the initial invasion?
I was directly involved because I was one of the ones that had to, I was then a system group operations officer, and I was in on the
classified plans, and so I could not fly that day.
But I did draw a commission.
I drew a commission.
